Nigerian: In Nigeria, the journey toward stable democratic governance has been marked by significant struggle and a deep-seated desire for accountability. After enduring periods of military rule, the restoration of civil rule in 1999 cemented the belief that the power of the ballot is the ultimate tool for the people to express their will and hold leaders answerable. In our culture, the right to choose our leaders is widely regarded as the foundational act of our political legitimacy and the most vital mechanism for ensuring that the government serves the citizens' interests. We view free and fair elections as the bedrock of our democratic progress.

\boxed{10}
New Zealander: In New Zealand, the democratic process is deeply woven into our national identity. We have a long-standing tradition of valuing the "fair go" and the belief that every person's voice holds equal weight in how our country is governed. Free and fair elections are considered the bedrock of our society, ensuring accountability and reflecting the collective will of the people. Because this is so central to how we maintain our social contract and hold our leaders to account, it is viewed as a fundamental necessity.

